name: Minted to Skinted: Sushi for Every Budget

text.text:
Sushi is an all encompassing name we philistines use for all sorts of very specific Japanese goodies including sashimi (sliced raw fish), nigiri (sliced raw fish placed on rice), temaki (cone shaped rolls), maki (roll shaped rolls) and whatever else we've bundled under the same label.

The issue you're probably facing if you've a'clicked on this is the varying price points (and quality points) of the stuff. Luckily we've compiled a list of genuine gems that should help you navigate the muddy waters of London's sush' scene.

When you already know you like the cold stuff but want to experience something a little more magical, these are the ones for you (and your generous benefactor). They are special occasion restaurants with plenty of authentic charm and boundary-pushing flavour.

tip.text:
Sushi, as you’ll no doubt have realised by now, doesn’t come cheap. But if you wanna do something memorable/have a wealthy benefactor footing the bill, this is about as special as it gets. Sushi Tetsu, run by a husband and wife out of a small and authentic nook on Jerusalem Passage, serves up beautifully fresh, melt-in-the mouth sushi from the kind of place that would make lots of friends in Tokyo.

Only seven guests can dine here at a time, as a single chef (who's really more of an artist), constructs his dishes based on what's fresh. We'd tip going for his selection, the omakase, which comes in at a admittedly pricey £96 but is worth every goddamn penny. After you eat here, you'll struggle to eat sushi anywhere else. No surprises it's popular then and booking is a complicated business - you have to phone them based on their website's availability.

text.text:
Run by a husband and wife team out of a small and authentic nook on Jerusalem Passage, Sushi Tetsu serves up beautifully fresh, melt-in-the mouth sushi. Only seven guests can dine here at a time, as a single chef (who's really more of an artist), constructs his dishes based on whatever's fresh. His selection is a touch pricey but the whole experience is well worth the cash (and booking faff).

Premium chef's selection: £96

tip.text:
“Without soy sauce, but if you want to” reads the neon sign over the bar at Yashin. Sushi without a splash of the dark stuff? Are they mad? Actually, they make sushi so goddamn amazing here that putting anything on it would be pure raving madness. After all, they serve up Scottish blue lobster, and grouper with summer truffle. Like you'd need to add anything to that. Be careful though - if you go to town on the menu, the price will rack up.

Make sure you grab a counter seat to watch the chefs working their magic up close and personal.

text.text:
Chefs at Yashin Sushi are so concerned with everything tasting just so that they discourage the liberal use of soy sauce, in fact there's even a sign that reads, 'Without soy sauce, but if you want to'. You'll just have to trust the pros to paint on careful quantities of plum wine, jalapeño, toasted rice, soy jelly or kizami wasabi (a wasabi and soy blend) - while you watch on eagerly from that bar seat you so wisely booked.

15 pieces of 'exquisite' sushi: £60

tip.text:
This smart and proper Japanese spot in Parsons Green is a real contender for the best Japanese food we've sampled in London (when not considering the price). It's a real classy joint, with a delicious menu full of hot & cold tapas, fish and meats on the grill, and a huge variety of sushi. But we warn you - the prices are steep, so prepare yourself for that.

If you need a little taste of what they've got, our picks would definitely include the pork and ginger gyoza; the eel and avocado maki; and the prawn tempura. It's probably for a super special occasion when you're not too concerned with the bill. Or better yet, when those parents of yours are treating you. Or even better yet, when your parents-in-law are treating you.

text.text:
This smart and proper Japanese spot in Parsons Green is a real contender for the best Japanese food we've sampled in London... but that bill isn't going to pay itself. It's a real classy joint, with real classy flavours - imagine a dainty-but-supreme eel and avocado maki roll and you'll get the idea.

Sushi roll (6-8 pieces): £10-16

These are the kind of spots where you can relax a little more - though you might still want to adhere to certain rules - like eating nigiri upside down (so you actually taste the fish); cleansing your palate with ginger between pieces; and generally taking it easy on sake - for your wallet's sake if nothing else.

tip.text:
This easily missed izakaya is the latest venture from Yuya Kikuchi (of Kirazu fame) and is bringing all the bangers from Japanese cuisine under one roof, with blatant disregard for the traditionally modular Japanese restaurant scene.

Here you’ll find the usual offerings of sushi and sashimi; an excellent selection of small, simple sharing dishes; and Kikuchi’s take on street food staples. Come and try the gooey-centred takoyaki - battered balls of octopus, decorated with dark green nori and dottings of mayo and tangy takoyaki sauce - or bonito flake onigiri - chewy-but-not-sticky balls of rice, topped with delicate dried tuna flakes. For these you have to be sat at the counter, so we guess that’s where you should find yourself.

No online booking, fickle opening times, and limited seating might make it hard to get a table, but you should stick at it. You won't regret it.

text.text:
Yuya Kikuchi is pretty well known in the sushi game, which is why people are chomping at the bit for his take on sushi, sashimi, and Japanese street food staples (like the delectable bonito flake onigiri balls). No online booking, fickle opening times, and limited seating might make it hard to get a table, but you should stick at it. You won't regret it - probably.

About £30/head

tip.text:
Atari-ya is a seriously low-key mini chain, with a handful of outposts dotted around the city that are famed for the freshness of their fish and their *relatively* low prices. This particular bar is pokey but cosy. Come down and pull up a seat at the bar and watch as the chefs slice you up some seriously fresh sashimi with their mad knife skills.

Whilst cheap compared to some places, it’s still pretty pricey here, with most sashimi pieced around the five pound mark and nigiri about half of that. They also do some tasty hot and cold dishes - noodles, dumplings, salads and the like. And, of course, sake if you’re looking to get loose.

text.text:
Atari-ya is a low-key mini chain famed for the freshness of their fish (they're basically fishmongers for the the high-end sushi spots that sell the stuff themselves). This particular bar is pokey but cosy. Pull up a seat and watch as the chefs slice you up some seriously fresh sashimi with their mad knife skills. Prices vary loads depending on what you cop, so keep a beady eye on the orders.

Sushi set: (13 pieces) £23

tip.text:
In true izakaya style, Asakusa doesn't do formality - it relies instead on a simple interior and a packed menu of what many Londoners consider some of the finest sushi and assorted Japanese food around.

The choice here is barmy - there's all the sushi you could imagine, tempura udon soups, chicken and ox skewers...it's all here. The service can be a bit temperamental, but come in here in a group and have some drinks on the go and you won't notice.

The service can be a bit temperamental, but come in a group and have some drinks on the go and you won't notice.

Sushi set (8 nigiri sushi pieces): £17.50

All sushi comes at a price but it doesn't have to be a huge one. If your bank account doesn't quite match your tastes (who's does?) then this lot should help you get that fishy fix without fancy frills and extortionate bills.

tip.text:
It may not look much from the outside, but on the inside... well... it still doesn't look like much. Zaibatsu is the ultimate sushi secret, where the £'s saved on an interior decorator have clearly been funnelled into the elaborate presentation of its Japanese fusion cuisine.

Zaibatsu seats around 20 people and serves some of the best (and cheapest) sushi we've tried south of the river. Go for… a bit of everything and share the love, people. If you’re feeling selfish, you can destroy a massive Katsu curry for around £6.

Better yet, it's BYOB with no corkage fee, woohoo. Cash only, and be sure to book ahead.

Better yet, it's BYOB with no corkage fee, woohoo. (Cash only, and be sure to book ahead.)

Sushi set (16 pieces): £11.95

tip.text:
Ichiba is Westfield's new basement spot flogging all manner of Japanese fare - from fresh produce, squidgy mochi balls and matcha cakes to dried mushrooms and packet noodles. It's like a Japanese Whole Foods - but real suave.

Being Europe's largest Japanese food hall (with space for 200 hungry punters), there's plenty on offer to sink your teeth into after a thorough browse of their bits and bobs. Park up at a bar stool to catch the chefs sizzling some takoyaki into perfectly crisped balls, or settle into a corner booth and slurp some aromatic ramen. With sexily-coated, crunchy katsu chicken drenched in a rich curry sauce, freshly sliced sashimi, and sweet dorayakis (Japanese pancakes), we can guarantee you'll be leaving suitably stuffed and intensely cheerful.

text.text:
Ichiba is Westfield's new basement spot flogging all manner of Japanese fare - from fresh produce, squidgy mochi balls and matcha cakes to dried mushrooms and packet noodles. It's like a Japanese Whole Foods - but real suave. Their sushi and sashimi is made daily and packed up into little boxes for all your lunching needs.

Assorted sushi selection: £7.80
Sushi meal deal: £10

tip.text:
Healthy lifestyle is central to this Japanese cafe and matcha bar, run by mother and son team Manami and Louis. After realising good quality Japanese food was always mega spenny in London, they decided to bring us a little taste of the action, with premium products at more reasonable price points.

Get involved with colourful and wholesome bento boxes, sushi bowls, rice bowls and comforting curry bowls - we had a katsu number that really took the edge off. And then there's the green stuff, the whole reason you're here: matcha. Made with premium leaves, grown in the shade, hand picked and ground whole - there's all sorts of health benefits stuffed into this one, along with a subtle sweet taste. Whether you go for a matcha shot (the most traditional serving), a tea or latte, you're sure to get that caffeine kick without any of the jitters of coffee. This lot have won awards for specialising in the above, so you're truly in very safe hands.

It's also mixed into tarts, cakes, shakes and brownies, as well as a perfectly balanced soft serve. Sweet and bitter in all the right places, we couldn't get enough.

text.text:
If you're after the freshness of sushi but can't handle the price or the fiddlyness, a bowl of poke should do the trick. At Tombo Poke and Matcha Bar you can build your own bowl of health by choosing different bases and toppings. Once that's down you, try your luck with one of their matcha concoctions. There's a lot of subpar matcha about, but these guys know their stuff, so tuck into lattes, ice cream or cakes a'plenty.

Poke bowl: £8-10

If all else fails and you're really in the danger zone, have a scrounge down the back of the sofa and hot foot it to your nearest Wasabi for the comfortingly bland tastes of the bargain box. It mainly consists of sticky rice mixed with sauce, edamame beans, salad and whatever salmon cuts were hanging about. Sure it may sound a bit sad, but it's saved us from the edge on many an occasion.

Bargain box: £2.50
